A Republican strategy to hinder Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and states that election fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die as a result of lightning strikes.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what happens in Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And in that same line a majority of American governments enacted, as of 2009, new laws that made the registration or voting process difficult.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote were introduced in 41 states during 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to a proof of U.S. citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day and withdraw their right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
Therefore, the Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people who earn less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years old do not have an identity document with a photograph.
And there's more.
In many states, students, the voters who vote the most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
Moreover, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use documents issued by such clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to make such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have enacted laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit Hispanic voting.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic party.
Republican lawmakers backed laws in 2011 that abolished voter registration on the same day in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service for voters who wished to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 resulted in the registration rate of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers passed laws in five other states that favored shortening the advance voting period.
For example, in the 2008 election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted ahead of time were African Americans, while the latter accounted for no more than 13% of the state’s voters.
In the case of Hispanics, the same thing happened.
These represent no more than 11% of voters, which is equivalent to 24% of citizens voting in advance.
However, whites, who make up 76 percent of the electorate, make up only 46 percent of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have fervently opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney’s Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
The damage could be limited in part.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have adopted such laws account for 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
