As far as the offices, such as the NK<0xC3><0x9A>, are concerned, the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors), with an organization similar to ours, with a school as well, the only thing is that in his case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The powers are also somewhat analogous, however, since Germany has a federal organisation, the courts of account are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, which here we call state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
Generally, I would not like to make a comparison without concrete data; however, Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be specified exactly where it is best.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
That’s for sure not, but, I repeat, I don’t like to make such comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as our model must face a large number of problems.
If that were not the case, you wouldn't benefit from collaborating with our office, would you?
As regards the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean for your Office? Is its impact manifest in any way?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex-post checks, there must be a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparation of future controls: we have started a new tool of "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public tenders, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process and the like are rectified.
Do you consider that the passage of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it is a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I believe that this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope it will be.
The problem that may arise is that the regulations are "hardened" and that it is impossible to comply with them.
Already under the previous regulations, the persons controlled were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and every law not respected in the area of public procurement meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to harden the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal failure, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this path leads us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDG would not disturb entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA1>varc system, referring to the fact of being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the <0xC5><0xA1>varc" system forbidden or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits something, then not even the Prime Minister of the government can prevent the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such controls and demand obligations.
You can say, “We change the law and allow it,” but you can’t say that we’re going to act like nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the rules are quite strict as to how to act formally, and this is how it should be to protect public competition.
But on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting the formal demands.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
