The architecture studio MVRDV shows that true adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly finished "mountain of books" - 2 photos
“I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and there’s finally something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the street.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: "Moreover, the building is beautiful."
But I wonder why we need a library nowadays.
We all have internet, tablets and e-books.
Nobody gets into those old-fashioned libraries for fun, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town on the outskirts of Rotterdam that barely deserves a brief visit, holds the dubious honor of having set a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counteract this embarrassing situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear represented on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that’s how policymakers decided that there was only one possibility to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture firm MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings at the same time cynical, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury looked around in perplexity and shrugged, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size into a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: “Dear fellow citizens:
Here it is, my proposal for Spijkenisse’s mountain of books, the so-called ‘Boekenberg’.
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain rises at the planned location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential buildings and townhouses.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town devoid of history, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather intuit a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheesecake.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountainous massif, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to embrace with the view, the annealed brick floor and elegant streetlights unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
When you look up you can see the park benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally book shelves are arranged along the facade and in the center a huge dark room opens up which is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to turn the classic spatial configuration upside down and take the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well taken advantage of: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserve the black shelves that assume the functions of wall cladding, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even the most up-to-date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the city of Spijkenisse.
And this is how one day, on a Frisian farm, we came across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands a plastic fabric of few millimeters thickness has been used as a base to hold the roots of the crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, to obtain plates four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mixture of new car and sneaker.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but in it you can also enjoy some tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
“Although it’s hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project when it comes to ecology,” Trouborst says.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Even though the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences located transversely to the glass facade serve to give shade and absorb most of the sun’s rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is the stuff of automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there too.
Likewise, the professor of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She describes the "Boekenberg" as the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way it is intended to fill, for the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; currently it has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
“I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows that your book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV studio has achieved a success in that queen discipline that in the specialized slang is known as "creation of an identity".
The town of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
Regardless of how young and uneducated he may be.
Finally a starting point for shaping your identity.
