Behind this name hides a name officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the true eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it is not clear that they will be given the reason.
“Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing law firm specializing in Far East protection rights violations.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to register their trademarks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and in place of Prada Prada-Kny is registered.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as happened to the sports goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a file cabinet in which it holds seats of the Beijing brand office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are department stores of several plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are of a different nature and, on behalf of his clients, he is fighting against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand.
The word originates from the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan".
It refers to women who have “fished” a rich man.
The Chinese government does not feel guilty.
“It’s detrimental to the business, you have to fight it,” Pattloch says.
“The brand makes waters, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage suffered by the image is enormous.”
The financial losses and procedural costs of the affected sectors are millionaire, especially in the case of luxury flagship products.
According to data from market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>15 billion a year, China is the third largest and fastest growing luxury goods market.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in the registration of trademarks is complicated and also requires a lot of money.
Processes can last up to nine years and the result is uncertain.
Pattloch speaks of cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because it had elapsed so long that the name at issue in the lawsuit had already become a “market reality.”
“If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged the plagiarist’s brand in China,” Pattloch said.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best-known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against the construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that was recently absorbed by the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That’s why today the Chinese can still use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo’s buyer, Geely, initially used a blue and white logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the case was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
Clothing maker Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo depicted a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
