Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a simple wooden house typical of the entire Caucasus region.
Sitting on the ground, she tirelessly moves a huge tub of butter.
Eight people live under a roof, including one of Mirzayeva’s sons and daughter, both of whom became grandparents long ago.
Two young children are also jumping from one side to the other.
In the kitchen they prepare tea for the guests, a tea that they serve in typical cups with domed shape.
Mirzayeva’s teeth are white and perfectly aligned and under the handkerchief she hides two long braids of dark blond hair that her son discovers us proudly.
I have always washed my hair with milk, so it has never fallen off and has kept its color.
"I've never used a shampoo either," Mirzayeva says.
The pension is enough to live
He has always eaten only what he produced on his own farm: tomatoes, potatoes and peas.
I’ve never been to a supermarket in my entire life.
Then she tells us about her husband, who was in the army.
The worst was the post-World War II era.
However, everything went back to normal when the "dear father", Heydar Aliyew, took control of the situation.
This kind of propaganda sounds weird in the mouth of an older woman.
However, in Azerbaijan the cult of the father figure of the nation, who runs his country as a dictator, knows no limits.
He remained in power until 2003, when he handed over the witness to his son Ilham.
At least the elderly in Azerbaijan do not know what poverty is.
Mirzayeva charges 230 manat (approximately the same amount in euros) as a monthly pension, an amount with which you can live well considering the situation here.
And perhaps Mirzayeva’s gray son is right: “in our culture the elders are very respected.”
They live in a big family, are loved, receive all the necessary care and are happy.
As if this wasn't reason enough to stay alive for many years...
In the Constitution, the expression “Human Rights” is missing.
The revolution has returned to Cairo.
Demonstrations that rival each other in Cairo show the tremendous division in which the country is immersed.
The future constitution, with sharia as its basis, is very controversial.
The Egyptian president spared no pathos.
“We need to overcome the transition.
