After the fall of the dictator up to 11,000 civilians were detained in military prisons.
As the draft states, the state must protect “the true essence of the Egyptian family” and “promote its morals and values.”
This is a formulation so imprecise in legal terms that with the help of this article state institutions could even control the contents of cinematography and literature.
To be clear, this is all about censorship.
Certainly, no article explicitly establishes equality between men and women.
Instead, another forbids offending or slandering the Prophet Muhammad and his legates.
However, it is unclear what an offense is and how it should be sanctioned.
Equally dubious is the formulation that forbids "offense to people"
Is a caricature of the president or a joke about a lawyer enough?
Question of interpretation, like many other things in the draft that has been presented to Morsi for his signature and that according to his words, "very soon" will be presented to the Egyptians to be submitted to a referendum.
