Saeda feels abandoned, also by the international community, which observes the ideological struggle that is taking place on the banks of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
This could turn against you.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns: "You are conceiving a monster that you will not be able to control."
Norwegian rakfisk: the most smelly fish in the world?
Norway's five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the success of the country has anything to do with its greed for an extremely smelly fish?
Take a series of over-cured cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a mountain of dirty, wet football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You can then smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway’s delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It is snowy. The landscape is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
The rakfisk is salted trout that is left to ferment in water for, depending on how smelly you prefer, up to a year.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, dedicated to this most, so to speak, captivating delicacy.
“You eat it raw and then drink a glass of aquavit from a drink,” says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also known as the “General of Rakfisk,” who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is kept in small buckets and drinking from a drink significant amounts of the drink.
“Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk,” says Havard.
Drinking can kill the smell.
I try some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it near the nose, it’s not bad; it’s not much different from a portion of sushi that has traveled a few miles by bus.
The rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different era, in which poverty plagued Norway and in which, before there was refrigeration, the fish was kept during the autumn immersed in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already well fermented, it is taken out and, evidently with the senses inactive due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Only a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Currently, the population is growing rapidly; more than 13 per cent are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a comprehensive system of social services.
A stream of inhabitants of Sweden, the old rival and even not too much richer than Norway, comes to this country to work.
The rakfisk is considered important, an essential, albeit rather smelly, part of Norway’s past.
It is among the most expensive dishes you can buy.
But, in fact, everything is expensive. A beer cane or a sandwich cost you a whopping <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>10 ($14) each.
Norway does not usually appear on the international news agenda and most Norwegians like it to be so.
Here people are still unwilling to pronounce the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as “the July 22 event.”
The Norwegians find it hard to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own was capable of committing such cruelty and murder.
Following much of Norway’s current wealth is the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world’s largest oil and gas industries.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, as she walks past trays of rakfisk, which, with its long blond hair and striking blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
“We are, as you say, wise people.”
His English, like that of most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like to show off."
Norway has managed its oil wealth very cautiously; everything except a small percentage of the money coming from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money they didn’t have in the years leading up to the global financial crisis, Norway kept the wallet tightly closed.
“As long as we can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we’re happy,” says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with a laugh.
I'm in the snow queuing to eat something; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is undoubtedly something different and quite juicy to taste.
But at night, that stinking fish comes back.
The hotel in which I stay is one of the many places where a rakfisk dinner is held in which diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A television has connected live with a presenter carrying a bow tie and who is surrounded by rakfisk dishes.
It looks like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There is laughter and applause.
A man falls from the chair, perhaps defeated by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the vapors of all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a tough start
As incoming Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant discusses the challenges the new president will face and the different expectations of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is especially bad nowadays.
In a city that, under the best circumstances, is already congested, a steel fence has been installed since Monday that cuts several of the main roads that lead to the city and is causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The aim, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their workplace, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will receive the presidential band and assume the management of the nation.
He faces a complicated task.
Mexico has been achieving good economic results during the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, but the country is immersed in a war against drug trafficking that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
“My government has a great commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Peña Nieto told President Barack Obama earlier this week in the Oval Office.
“I’m going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal.”
Prior to meeting with the U.S. president, Mr. Peña’s previous political experience was as governor of his home state of Mexico.
A heavily populated and rapidly growing state, it surrounds the capital; opinions about the new leader are divided in this territory in which he used to move.
A sincere man
In the bucolic city of Valle del Bravo, for example, he is remembered with affection.
Its residents attribute to it the merit of the growth of tourism in the place and of the construction of infrastructures.
To get to the city you can drive by one of Mr. Peña Nieto’s new roads, which is a huge improvement compared to the cracked and bumpy roads that were rehabilitated.
You can also see plaques with his name at the entrance of a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We trust that he will achieve real and lasting change," says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, deputy of the party of Mr. Peña Nieto, the PRI.
“In particular, when it comes to security and the economy, we look forward to the interesting and real change that our country so badly needs.”
After an uninterrupted period of 81 years in power, the PRI was overthrown by Vicente Fox in 2000.
The deputy Olvera admits that, after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, within the party there are many expectations regarding Enrique Peña Nieto.
It also rejects the opposition’s qualification of the new president’s lack of essence.
“He is a very sincere man, very committed and with an excellent vision of the country.
He’s a fantastic statesman and, above all, he’s a person who knows how to listen.”
However, on the other side of the state that’s not the impression many people have about their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobblestone streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
Hidden under highway stretches is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems of the municipality are also hard and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called upon to help in the fight against drug gangs operating in neighborhoods and violence against women is especially serious.
In a desert plot, located next to a garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left abandoned in just the last two years.
More than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was the governor, a rate much higher than that of Ciudad Juárez, unfortunately famous for its violence and a place that is synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
Critics of Mr. Peña Nieto say, at best, that he failed to address the problem of femicide while in office.
Most critics accuse his administration of turning a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the deteriorated neighborhood, Irinea Buendía has to make efforts to contain tears while showing me photographs of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the facts, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes her partner murdered her.
“When I arrived at his house, it seemed as if his body had been cleaned,” Mrs. Buendía recalls.
"There were signs that she had been beaten and the rigor mortis had already appeared."
While her mother tells the story, a photograph of Mariana looks from the walls, next to a cross in which a single word is read: Justice.
However, that’s exactly what the family says has been denied.
“The state authorities have treated me as if I were an old gossip, a rioter, a whistleblower.
What they want is for one to simply accept what they say and shut up.”
“But that cannot be so when there have been so many irregularities and so much negligence,” he says.
The presidential band that President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will come with a huge responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crimes in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has promised to give them priority during his tenure.
“I hope it’s the same kind of president that he was when he was governor,” says the PRI deputy Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
However, that is precisely what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear most.
Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to deal with Bradley Manning’s allegations of abuse while in prison
Trial centers on Manning's time at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's imprisonment was severe
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now claims to have suffered while in military detention.
During the prosecution’s pre-trial interrogation of Manning in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein said records of weekly visits of unit officers Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he was receiving.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence ' s request for dismissal of the case given that his imprisonment had been harsh and that this had already meant sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning had testified that he had thought of committing suicide while in detention.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
WikiLeaks later published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
In Friday’s hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms officers were filling out after Manning’s visits during his arrest at Quantico Military Prison, where he was incarcerated under maximum incarceration from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers would have asked Manning questions and written down his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had rated the caregiver’s treatment as “excellent” and the treatment received at the facility in general as “very professional.”
The forms show no allegations of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers visiting him had spoken about those issues and had indicated to him that they would be dealt with, but that they had not recorded those issues on the register.
“They were writing ‘no incidents’ (after talking about the problems) but this doesn’t necessarily mean that I hadn’t mentioned any problems,” Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why she had not denounced the treatment she received during the January 2011 meeting with a board charged with examining the suicide intentions she had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was.
The military said it had put him under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below that of surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was okay and (want) to stop being under injury prevention ... so that I could enjoy what, in my view, is a better quality of life,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison located at the Marines' base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage,” Manning said Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning said that once transferred to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, alone.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from outside pointing at his eyes while he slept.
He said that if the caretakers could not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning’s treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he made in Thursday’s statement that, after being forced to sleep naked one night in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates.
Manning had testified that he had never been given a chance to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge’s interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the order given to him by the caretaker that he should drop the blanket with which he could have been covered, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic in his underwear or his flip-flops to injure himself but had not.
Manning testified that he had removed his underwear, flip-flops and glasses from his cell that night.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he had during his time in prison and drastically reduce his sentence should he be convicted in the war council, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to have Manning plead guilty to misdemeanor offenses and defend other allegations deemed too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was detained in accordance with the rules applicable to any detainee who is in maximum custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally provoking the publication of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information and theft of property or public records.
If convicted of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He says many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; says they remember Mexicans from those difficult times
Navarrette remarks that Mexican-Americans are trapped between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, he had barely gone down the esplanade and arrived at the immigration processing area and was already totally confused.
Some signs indicated the way to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" and another for "Extranjeros".
I sat there for a few seconds without being sure where I should go.
Growing up in Central California, I’ve been called “Mexican” all my life.
This is ethnic shorthand, just as my friends in Boston refer to themselves as “Irish” or my friends in New York call themselves “Italians.”
Later I decided to be "Mexican-American."
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather’s homeland, shorthand or scripts were not necessary.
He was simply an American.
I speak Spanish. Good enough to handle myself during an interview in this language.
But I don’t have the vocabulary level of a native and I can’t get rid of my American accent.
So I took my American passport and put myself in the queue of foreigners.
I thought about that moment this week when the President-elect of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda of the day, as always when the leaders of these two countries meet, included: immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also eager to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why at the moment it is so likely that a Mexican stays in Mexico that he ventures to go to the United States.
It wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create in North America a trade bloc in the style of the European Union.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting drug cartels in Mexico, although he gave no details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half of their territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not minutes, the elements that remind them are everywhere.
So, the moment a U.S. official says anything that carries the slightest criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the sons of Moctezuma go to war.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that really poses a challenge is the one they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking about resentment?
There's a lot of it.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for which it is not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, at some point in our family tree, there was a person, maybe the father or mother or one of the grandparents, who was closed the door to opportunities in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time that person fit a certain profile: dark skin, low level of education, from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not to Mexico.
And, even though we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and had good jobs, we can never lose sight of what we are living is that, the American dream, and not the Mexican one.
Sometimes our identity may not be clear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the elite of the ruling class do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look over our shoulders as if we were from a lower category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In his view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have left.
And now we would not find ourselves trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but, still, as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came legally to the United States when she was a child, reminds me that there is this friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more solidly who they are and the latter this bothers them.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she considers herself part of the two countries.
In the meantime, many Mexican-Americans I know feel that they are not part of either.
We love to hear the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of every country, but you are not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico they see us as Americans.
And in the United States we are considered Mexicans.
Now, to complicate things further, as I learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as improvised “ambassadors” of Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our fellow Americans how fantastic it is to visit that country and we would pressure political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much resentment.
And, with wage inequality, rampant corruption, and drug violence, many of us aren’t so sure it’s a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're going to be left alone with this idea, friends.
That's fair.
If some Mexicans are still unprepared to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful about how their relatives were treated much less long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexicans" than I thought.
Old Battles, New Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could well be an unlikely basis for peace
Can there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
Amid the useless and usual discussions about who started first, heaps of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But even though Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their old conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left everything to pieces whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have become trapped in the regional turmoil.
Perhaps this will make their struggle even more bloody than before.
However, there is reason to think that his deadly deadlock situation could unravel.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems currently very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 is maintained, this week’s clashes have reinforced the falcons on both sides.
Hamas leaders, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has been beaten up.
And despite killing some of its leaders and putting pressure on Gaza’s 1.7 million people in one of the most miserable and populous corners of the planet, Israel has failed to wipe out Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its relentless rivals Fatah, the most moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders could come to the conclusion that time plays in their favor.
Since Islamists have been gaining influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a reborn regional power that had previously been Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has embraced the cause of Hamas, as has Qatar, one of the wealthiest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Exultant Hamas members say the Islamist crescent is encircling Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where the Hezbollah party-militia dominates, through Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist tendency could overthrow Bashar Assad, to reach Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Especially on the southern flank of Israel, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and fundamental of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, did not have much time for Hamas.
Instead, the Muslim Brotherhood is Hamas’s cousins and its leaders depend more on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, it is possible that Hamas will emerge as a protagonist that cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, Israel’s hard wing will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military question is concerned, they have put Hamas in its place.
Israel’s Iron Dome anti-missile system has proven its effectiveness and many of Hamas’ missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep quieter... for some time.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the United States is firmer than ever; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for starting the latest wave of violence.
