Tobacco generic packaging law goes into effect in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and diseased parts of the body appear on packets of a dull green color, which are the same for all tobacco brands
Australia’s pioneering generic tobacco and packaging law comes into force and replaces the logos and colors of the brands with a dull olive-green wrapper, frightening images of diseased body parts and depictions of children and babies who are ill because they are the children of smoking parents.
With the exception of the different images and health warnings, the only difference between the boxes, mandatory since Saturday, are the names of the brands, all of them printed in a small font type.
It is the world’s strictest regime for tobacco packaging.
Australia’s federal government says the goal is to deter young people from smoking by eliminating the traits that make this habit glamorous.
It relies on studies that show that if a person has not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that he will never do so.
“It can be seen that children, even from a very young age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand,” said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies showing, for example, how girls related the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest rates of smokers in the world and these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals too much, other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry has exerted enormous pressure against the law.
Tobacco companies said the law would encourage the black market for tobacco, in which cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
“The legislation will have serious unintended consequences,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco in Australia.
It will increase the amount of tobacco that counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring to sell on the streets of Australia.
Others say their business has benefited from the passage of the law.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said the lawsuit for silicone skins and covers to cover the nasty images of the boxes had skyrocketed almost from scratch two months ago, when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a challenge to the law in Australia's Supreme Court.
Ms. Ha said that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale establishments and was expecting more stocks.
“It’s a good business for us.”
According to experts, the possible obstacle is the popularity of social media among the demographic sector to which the plan is aimed.
Following a series of Australian laws banning television advertising and sports sponsorship and forcing most sellers not to put cigarettes in plain sight, tobacco marketing has gone online.
Australia has banned Internet advertising to local businesses and websites, but cannot restrict it on foreign websites.
“If you market tobacco and you only have this little window left to promote your products, the online space is the most compelling place to be,” said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noted an increase in reviews of brands from “walking citizens” posted on social media websites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
One might wonder if this is just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigars and has taken the trouble to make a video or if some marketing company is behind it all.
Australia’s British American Tobacco said the industry is more focused on what the new regulations involve than on marketing.
The industry has even come to pay for Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to refuse the new rules; these countries are claiming to the World Trade Organization that trade is being unfairly restricted, despite the fact that neither of these countries has a significant volume of trade with Australia.
The WTO is likely to issue a resolution in mid-2013.
Plibersek said the government had held talks with other countries that are considering enforcing similar tobacco packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to introduce the compulsory inclusion of images in boxes.
They are currently compulsory in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
In Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India, tougher laws are being considered.
In Australia, many smokers are challenging.
“Photography doesn’t affect me.
I just don't listen to them."
“You take the cigar and you save the package,” Victor El Hage says as he buys a package with the image of a tumor in his mouth.
“Frankly, there’s only one reason I’d quit smoking: for my daughter.”
James Yu, manager of the King of the Pack store in central Sydney, says uniform boxes make it harder for him to put them on the shelves.
“It usually took me an hour to unpack a delivery; now it takes me four,” Yu says.
“The government should have totally banned tobacco and then, that’s it, okay, it’s over and we close the store,” he says as he raises his hands up.
In a constantly connected world, it’s not so bad to get a little bored
During this year’s Thanksgiving holidays, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying on had a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is quite boring, even if you have means to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, not to mention duty-free shops.
But more and more academics and child development experts are praising the benefits of boredom.
According to them, it is good that both we and our children get bored from time to time.
Boredom forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since, currently, most of us are connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits that boredom brings.
So should we accept boredom with good cheer?
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
And no.
But, we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of the book Boredom: A Lively History, published in 2011 by Yale University Press, says, it is not so.
“In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive,” he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about boredom dating back to the 1st century AD.
We also need to consider how we define boredom.
“The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in a variety of ways,” says John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the published research and raising the idea before a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of “desiring, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fills you.”
He states that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "the disruption of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time is slowly passing."
Boredom can sound terribly like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that although they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a matter of environment or the world, while people who are depressed see the problem as their own.
Sometimes we think we’re bored, when what actually happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a journal article.
Some groups listened in the adjoining room to a full-volume TV show that had no relation, others listened with the low volume, so that it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the show with the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; they struggled to concentrate, but were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
“When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, disruption of attention can lead to boredom,” said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
“On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, like spotting faulty parts on a manufacturing line, music that distracts you can help you not get bored.”
“In fact, we currently know that moving or scribbling, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help combat it, as they make that person physically more alert.”
“Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to stand still,” says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it’s like to get bored at some point: the delay of a plane, a monotonous speaker, an especially boring movie.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed a “boring trend scale” in the 1980s.
The scale includes issues like “many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous” and “there are so many things that interest me that I don’t have time to do it all.”
Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that, using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external and more varied stimulation.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day through a search.
He found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored while they were at school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they were not at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that "adolescence is a period when boredom reaches its highest," in large part because both children and teens are not given much control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: Is it good to get bored?
Sometimes it is not, since, taken to the extreme, it can make us expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as making bets or falling into the consumption of substances as a method to combat it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
“Boring is the way your brain tells you that you should be doing something else,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn’t always know what’s most appropriate.
If you are bored and use that energy to play the guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
“So, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may not be bored anymore, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or dosage himself,” says Professor Fenske.
And "that ability to dosage applies to other situations," he says.
Your child not only learns to entertain themselves, but learns to control themselves better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn’t be too critical of him either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant noise of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“In our view, we need to get bored more, but boredom is a desire that is too distressing and disturbing to relate to something worthwhile,” she says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated,” he says, “it’s hard to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops.”
Colorado: No Instruction Book for New Marijuana Consumption Law
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old student at a community institute and footballer in southeast Colorado, faces criminal prosecution for something that will soon be legal statewide: the possession of some marijuana stones and a pipe he used to smoke it.
Orozco says that one day in September, he and some friends were driving through Lamar, in the plains near the Kansas border, when they were stopped by the police.
Police found marijuana in the car and a time later Orozco received a subpoena for possession of drugs and related items (minor offenses each involving a fine of 100 U.S. dollars) informing him of the date of the trial.
“They treat us like criminals,” Orozco says.
And they are?
In the weeks of uncertainty following Colorado’s vote to legalize the possession of small amounts of marijuana for recreational use, the answer in hundreds of minor drug-holding lawsuits depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of misdemeanors for marijuana possession are being overturned both here and in Washington state, where a similar measure was passed.
Police departments have stopped filing charges against those over 21 for small-scale possession, which will be legally passed once the law comes into effect in the coming weeks.
But Colorado’s most conservative district attorneys have pledged to move forward with marijuana possession cases and are still citing people.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the western mountains, are voting to prevent the opening of recently licensed marijuana stores in their communities.
“This is all changing so quickly that I don’t know what’s next,” said Daniel J. Oates, chief of police at Aurora, just east of Denver.
Those in charge of regulations in Washington state are also turning the issue around.
And they continue to seek advice to establish a system of production, manufacturing, distribution and sales licensing – all before the deadline, December 1, 2013.
They say that, for better or worse, Colorado is ahead of most states in regulating the use of marijuana, first for therapeutic purposes and now for recreational use.
“Colorado has a more regulated market, so it will be a good guide,” said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Alcohol Control Commission.
But Mr. Smith admits that any place or system can only make suggestions about what might work.
“There is no real precedent that can serve as a model,” he says.
The Washington law, dubbed I-502, comes into force on December 6, which also leaves a year during which you will swim between two waters, since the licensing system in that state will not yet exist, but the possession will be legal.
In addition, there are some delicate mechanical issues that need to be resolved during this period, such as how to maintain a balance between the state’s requirement to provide “adequate access” to authorized marijuana and its prohibition of conducting cannabis businesses within 300 meters of schools, parks, children’s playgrounds or children’s centers.
“Nowhere will it be more difficult to locate a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a newly created research group.
On November 21, Oates, Aurora’s police chief, e-mailed his police officers that the city prosecutor would stop filing charges for minor misconduct for possession of marijuana to people over the age of 21 and that the police would stop filing charges against those crimes “with immediate effect.”
Police Chief Oates said they would enforce the city’s regulations regulating the cultivation of marijuana for therapeutic purposes and that they would continue to prosecute drug traffickers and vendors.
In Weld County, northern Colorado, district attorney Ken Buck represents a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to prosecute marijuana possession cases, mainly to pressure consumers to decide to receive treatment.
Currently, 119 people face charges for possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many of them have other charges.
“Our office has an obligation to bring legal action against those misdemeanors that at the time they occurred were criminal,” Buck said in a statement.
The response has been tricky even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana legalization initiative.
Grand Junction police, the county’s largest city, no longer cite adults for possession of small amounts.
Pete Hautzinger, the county district attorney, supported this decision, but also decided not to dismiss any of the pending possession cases.
“I don’t think he’s wasting his time in continuing to enforce the law until it changes,” he said.
Although 55 percent of voters supported the measure, it was never considered that bringing recreational marijuana use to the government and the judiciary was going to be easy.
The contradictory reactions that arise throughout the state reveal a marked ambivalence among officials regarding the great environmental experiment in this state.
“This is a cultural barrier to district attorneys,” said Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney representing those accused of marijuana possession and a local spokesperson for the National Organization for the Reform of the Marijuana Act.
“They’ve spent so much time taking people to court that, in reality, they still can’t accept that it’s legal,” he said.
As the first states to consider small amounts of marijuana in the same way as if it were alcohol, Colorado and Washington are preparing to become the nationwide test cases for drug legalization.
While lawyers and state officials have a new frontier of legal sales, they also look forward to receiving directions from the federal government, which still envisions considering the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Proponents of marijuana legalization are hopeful that the Justice Department will give in.
Although there have been some prominent arrests of patients and sellers of marijuana for therapeutic purposes, the federal government has mostly allowed businesses to sell marijuana for these purposes in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
“While anti-drug agents are likely not to throw down doors to confiscate a small bag of drugs, they will likely be reluctant to allow state-regulated stores for the sale of marijuana for recreational use, permitted under the new law,” said Kevin A. Sabet, a former anti-drug policy adviser to the Obama administration.
Several Colorado cities aren’t waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before election day, some local governments passed moratoriums on any new marijuana stores, even though it will be about a year before any of them can open.
Last week, the western city of Montrose adopted a six-month ban and is likely to pass it next week.
“We don’t want to put ourselves in a situation where we authorize someone and then have a serious problem at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
"Our community voted against this amendment.
We are studying in favor of what the community voted for versus voting in favor of what the state voted for."
A lot of questions arise about this.
Petronella Wyatt: "I was harassed to get kicked out of Oxford for being a Tory"
College students are not attacked for their views just now
I don’t remember any time in my life when I wasn’t dreaming of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had been in what I assumed was the best place in the world to learn, a contemporary-era Greek symposium that fostered the two pillars of civilization: free thinking and tolerance.
However, within two weeks of taking my place at Worcester College in the late 1980s to pursue a history degree, I had already packed my bags, which triggered the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and started crying.
My friends were baffled.
The Evening Standard newspaper claimed that I had given up because I did not tolerate some college classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer A. N. Wilson joked that I had left because I was forced to drink in peeled cups.
The truth was less fun.
I ran away from there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my extravagant name, or the fact that it came from a private school.
I was harassed for only one reason, which at the cradle of the supposed illustration was somewhat intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the Conservative Party.
You may be wondering what that is now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of center-right students is suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred of Conservative students is such in Oxford that, last week, a group of them claimed the same level of equal rights as homosexuals, the disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College’s JCR (grouping of undergraduate students) claim that they are “often seriously sidelined, personally attacked and treated as unpleasant people” for their political ideas.
They want to create a position on their college’s equal opportunities committee to make sure they can express their views freely.
Their situation was not favored by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" about student politics and portraying the Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It showed graduate student Joe Cooke, former chairman of the Conservative Party Association at the University of Oxford (OUCA), in a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a cane with a silver grip.
At other universities, conservative students say they are treated like “Turkish heads” by introducing higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, 20, vice president of the University of Nottingham Conservative Party Association, stated in a Sunday newspaper that "there is a growing left-wing trend in universities.
“People assume we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other.”
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi who filed the motion for greater protection, says the environment is "uncomfortable," while Stephanie Cherill, 19, an elected president of the OUCA, says the attitude of JCR members toward people who are center-right has worsened.
“This poses a threat to the intellectual debate environment as well as the well-being of members,” he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford I was more alone than one.
I entered college in September 1986, I was a terribly shy 18-year-old.
The hatred towards the Conservative Party was at its highest point.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an "honoris causa" title after cuts in funding for higher education.
The atmosphere would have shocked any Stalinist.
Already during the first days of the week of welcoming new university students, when the new students meet and meet the professors, I received a sample of the bitterness that awaited me.
I found that the professors not only turned a blind eye to the mockery of conservative university students, but also willingly participated in it.
The policy of the miners’ strike, privatization and the government’s opposition to the apartheid sanctions in South Africa reached as far as the wooden halls of the seminary.
The first one I attended had to translate into English French texts of the eighteenth century and I was not prepared for what came next.
“Miss Wyatt,” said Professor Harry Pitt (already deceased), “please translate the first paragraph.”
Not one of them.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake dough, knew well how to expel bad bile.
“Do Thatcherists refuse to learn French, or are they just fools?” he asked.
The other students laughed.
My eyes were burning with the tears I was trying to contain.
“I suggest you go to French classes in your free time, as long as you’re not too busy meeting people,” Pitt grunted.
I returned to my room like a soul in sorrow.
That night I sat alone at dinner time in college; then I felt a slight pat on the back.
He was a second-year English student named James who applied as a member of the OUCA.
“I know who you are,” he said politely.
“I’m afraid that’s how it goes.
They mess with anyone suspected of being Tory.
For me it's very complicated, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so for you it'll be even worse.
Many Tories newcomers appear to be Labour.”
Later, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to disguise.
I insisted that I disagreed with everything Mrs. Thatcher was saying.
That trick turned out to be useless.
A first-year student of Philosophy, Politics, and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said, “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You are contaminated.”
Other students adopted this song.
I became the dirty pervert.
"How do the Tories have sex?" one asked.
"They beat each other up, don't they?"
I felt the same way that homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 1960s.
Could you ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to hang out with people who thought like me only after dark?
Should I become Labour and suppress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me presented themselves as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History destined for my college.
They hated him for being not only from the Conservative Party, but also Thatcher’s foreign policy adviser and one of the people who wrote his speeches to him.
I was barely there.
He detested the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-determinist vision of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he said.
I began to move daily from Oxford to my parents’ house in London, finding refuge in my more open-minded family and friends.
I told my dad I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he was studying there in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said sadly.
"They would never do that, not there among my dear dreamy needles.
Even my communist friends have always had an impeccable attitude.”
His sore eyes began to blur.
"Give him another chance.
I'm sure they did it just to joke.
My heart would break if you left him.”
Tired of so many trips to London, my emotional resilience was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and had renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another professor of history had implied, quite seriously, that I was an “enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Red with shame inside, I admitted that my parents had “brainwashed me” and called them “dumb old men.”
The truce lasted a short time.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my college career at Oxford.
At that time my father wrote two weekly columns in Murdoch’s press.
My door was locked.
I was inside huddled in fear and, after five minutes, my persecutors gave up.
When they left, I packed my bags and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
Maybe you call me weak weeping.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such a level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, which has not only trained 14 Conservative Party prime ministers but is now hiding behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to notoriety"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino: Master of Sewing", which opened this week in London, ABC speaks with Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, former residence of Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition on Valentino Garavani.
The designer has recognized him during the inauguration of "Valentino: Master of Sewing", an apotheosis retrospective that brings together more than 130 haute couture dresses created by his "maison" over the last 50 years.
“I love this palace,” he says with his unmistakable Italian accent.
This exhibition is the culmination of a story whose sole protagonist is "il Signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without his distinguished clients.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the rarefied and distant world of the nobility.
In the first room of this exhibition, open until next March 3, private letters and photos with the signature of the most pomegranate of the aristocracy, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, through Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margaret of England.
Valentino teaches these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from the humble couturier of the city of Voghera, in northern Italy, to the idol of the international jet-set.
Being in love with royalty is not bad.
“At least they don’t put out the butts of their hair on your magnificent carpet like some beautiful pop music celebrities do,” says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 60s and 70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular host and entertains with generosity and elegance.
“We all loved to be invited to their chalet in Gstaad,” explains the ex-wife of “Heini” Thyssen, intimate of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to notoriety.
And yet, he's a star.
Valeria Mazza, wearing a Valentino
Argentinian model Valeria Mazza also doesn’t forget the fashion designer’s charisma.
Many years ago, after a parade in Piazza di Spagna, in Rome, we went to have dinner at his apartment.
There were twenty people, including Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
In every detail of the floor, the decoration, the food, the music, everything was seen and felt his spirit.
"Every one of the guests made us feel important and loved," recalls the "top model", who began working with him during the Haute Couture Week in Paris in 1995.
“It never goes out of style because its designs are works of art,” he concludes.
Alcurnia parade
Garavani’s life is not a story of obsessions, but of well-required loves.
He loves people with good education and better degrees, and they love him.
One of the galleries of Somerset House has been transformed into a glamorous catwalk of sixty meters long that proposes a change of roles: the visitor takes the place of the models and must parade down the catwalk to contemplate a "audience" of dreams that wears masterpieces of Valentino, such as the dress that Jackie Kennedy chose for her wedding dresses and the ones that he used.
Names such as Sibylle of Luxembourg, Gloria von Thurn und Taxis, Mette-Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria or Sophia of Habsburg shine in this audience of mannequins.
Naty Abascal and the Fashion Designer, 2006
Many of those clients say that the first Valentino is like the first love, "impossible to forget".
I remember it perfectly.
It was a trouser, a shirt, a "gillette" vest and a jacket from the autumn-winter 1971-1972 collection.
“It was a gift he gave me,” says Naty Abascal, one of the designer’s muses.
“I prefer him over others for his femininity, for his great love of women, because he enhances our beauty,” she added.
I really like the colors you use, they have great light and are "donors" to the face.
