The world’s toughest job: Kawah Ijen’s human mules
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano are risking their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living pulling sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to descend every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulphurous gas emanating from the Earth’s bowels solidifies when it comes into contact with air.
After pulling out large rocks of sulfur, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two baskets of bamboo that he carries on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
They are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to ascend at the step of a turtle, keeping the balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall down the precipice.
They know that any trip could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell down the cliffs of the Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract
Once upstairs, they make their way among the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, fatiguedly loading the heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters above sea level.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) for every kilogram of sulfur.
It is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As usual, it is to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually carries out three daily transports.
It takes three hours in each and ends up ground, but they allow you to collect 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such an inhuman effort, it is three times as much as you would earn on the field.
"The miners' salary is very high here, where the coffee collection is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros), "says the porter, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the cut was not that hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as strong as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I have brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, has difficulty breathing, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been playing with his skin in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to pass the bill despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, has difficulty breathing, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
This is the price you have to pay to achieve your dream.
“I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished for life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead does the work of a mule.
Sharing an unclean wooden hut with other porters, it rises every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not cease to flow at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends to the crater illuminating himself with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
About 400 carriers carry the sulfur baskets over their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its dripping benefits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur extraction to save costs or supply any equipment to carriers, who work on their own and at both weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera that, along with the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for the beasts and not for the people,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old heavyweight carrier who has been on the Kawah Ijen for three decades since he left school.
Capable of lifting up to 110 kilos, she says she will endure working "everything she can" because she needs the money to educate her three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and barks the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious illnesses... beyond, of course, their usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, knee pains and sores in the shoulders, which have been malformed by the weight of the cestas.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his companions pull 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks move to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat road through the weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30, also works carrying sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the toughest trades in the world: that of the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
